Experiment Title

Controlling a Stepper Motor Using Arduino MKR WiFi 1010, ULN2003 Driver,
and Blynk IoT

Components Used

1. Arduino MKR WiFi 1010

The Arduino MKR WiFi 1010 is a microcontroller board with built-in Wi-Fi capability.
 It acts as the main controller in this experiment, receiving commands from the
  Blynk application and controlling the stepper motor accordingly.

2. Stepper Motor (28BYJ-48)

The 28BYJ-48 is a low-cost stepper motor that rotates in precise steps rather than
 continuously. This allows accurate control of the motor's position and direction.
  In this experiment, the motor rotates clockwise or counter-clockwise based on
  commands received from the Blynk app.

3. ULN2003 Motor Driver

The ULN2003 driver module is used to interface the stepper motor with the Arduino.
 Since the Arduino cannot supply enough current to drive the motor directly,
  the ULN2003 acts as a current amplifier and switching circuit, enabling safe and
   reliable motor operation.

4. Blynk IoT Application

Blynk is a cloud-based IoT platform that allows users to remotely control hardware
 using a smartphone. In this experiment, two buttons were created in the Blynk app
  to control the rotation direction of the stepper motor.

5. Wi-Fi Network

The Wi-Fi network provides internet access for communication between the Arduino
 MKR WiFi 1010 and the Blynk cloud server. This allows the motor to be controlled
  remotely through the mobile application.

6. WiFiNINA Library

The WiFiNINA library enables the MKR WiFi 1010 to connect to wireless networks
 and communicate over the internet.

7. BlynkSimpleWiFiNINA Library

This library allows communication between the MKR WiFi 1010 and the Blynk platform,
 making it possible to receive commands from the mobile application.

8. Stepper Library

The Stepper library provides functions for controlling stepper motors.
 It simplifies motor control by allowing the user to define the motor speed
  and the number of steps to rotate.

9. Blynk Buttons (Virtual Pins V0 and V1)

Two button widgets were used in the Blynk application:

V0: Rotates the motor clockwise.
V1: Rotates the motor counter-clockwise.

What the Experiment Did

The experiment demonstrated the remote control of a stepper motor using the
 Arduino MKR WiFi 1010 and the Blynk IoT platform.

The MKR WiFi 1010 connected to a Wi-Fi network and established communication with
 the Blynk cloud server using an authentication token. Two buttons were configured
  in the Blynk application using Virtual Pins V0 and V1.

When the user pressed the V0 button, the BLYNK_WRITE(V0) function was triggered,
 causing the stepper motor to rotate 512 steps clockwise. When the V1 button was
  pressed, the BLYNK_WRITE(V1) function executed and rotated the motor 512 steps
   counter-clockwise.

The motor speed was set to 10 RPM using the motor.setSpeed(10) command.
 Through the Blynk app, users could remotely control the direction of the stepper
  motor from anywhere with an internet connection.

Importance of the Experiment

This experiment is important because it demonstrates how IoT technology can be used
 to remotely control electromechanical devices.

The experiment helped in understanding:

Wireless communication between a microcontroller and a cloud platform.

Remote motor control using a smartphone application.

The operation of stepper motors and their precise positioning capabilities.

The role of motor driver circuits such as the ULN2003.

Integration of hardware, software, and cloud services in an IoT system.

Such systems are widely used in industrial automation, robotics, smart manufacturing,
 automated doors, conveyor systems, and home automation projects.

4. Conclusion

The experiment successfully demonstrated the remote control of a stepper motor
using an Arduino MKR WiFi 1010, a ULN2003 motor driver, and the Blynk IoT platform.

 By pressing buttons on the Blynk application, the user could rotate the motor
  clockwise or counter-clockwise through commands sent over the internet.

   The project provided practical experience in IoT communication, motor control,
    and cloud-based automation. Overall, it showed how connected devices can be
     controlled remotely, forming the basis for more advanced smart automation and
      robotics applications.